FIGS. 1A and 1B illustrate an apparatus constructed in accordance with the present invention for stacking flat folded cartons of non-uniform thickness and automatically packing those stacked cartons into a shipping container;


FIG. 2 is a perspective view of a folded carton adapted to be stacked and inserted into a container box by the apparatus of FIGS. 1A and 1B;


FIGS. 3A-3C are perspective views of portions of the first, second and third bins;


FIG. 4A is a side view of an interrupt finger assembly of the apparatus illustrated in FIGS. 1A and 1B;


FIG. 4B is a side view of a portion of the finger assembly illustrated in FIG. 4A;


FIG. 4C is a view taken along view line 4C--4C in FIG. 4B;


FIG. 4D is a top view of the interrupt finger assembly of the present invention;


FIG. 4E is a view taken along view line 4E--4E in FIG. 4D;


FIG. 5 is a top view of the first bin;


FIG. 6 is a top view of the second bin;


FIG. 7 is a top view of the slug forming station of the apparatus illustrated in FIGS. 1A and 1B;


FIG. 8 is a view taken along view line 8--8 in FIG. 7;


FIG. 9 is a top view of a slug receiving basket and the reciprocating carriage to which it is mounted;


FIG. 10 is a view taken along view line 10--10 in FIG. 9;


FIG. 11 is a top view of the two second side guides and a piston/cylinder assembly for effecting pivotable movement of the side guides;


FIG. 12 is a view taken along view line 12--12 in FIG. 11;


FIG. 13 is a front view of a sheet inserter and a piston/cylinder unit for effecting pivotable movement of the sheet inserter;


FIG. 14 is a view taken along view line 14--14 in FIG. 13;


FIG. 15 is a plan view of the slug unload station;


FIG. 16 is a view taken along view line 16--16 in FIG. 15;


FIG. 17 is a view taken along view line 17--17 in FIG. 15; and


FIG. 18 is a perspective view of a shipping container packed with two slugs of folded cartons.
